Rights, Resources, and Social Justice Speaker Series - Collective Action, Property Rights, and Development: Making the Links, Department of Environmental Studies | NYU                                         NEW YORK UNIVERSITY       ARTS AND SCIENCE       COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE       GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE                                     Printer Friendly                            Back to Events         Collective Action, Property Rights, and Development: Making the Links            ,     Location: 194 Mercer Street, Room 305   Property rights are all the rage in development circles. But what are the real links between property rights and sustainable livelihoods for the poor? And what kind of property rights are we talking about? What role does collective action have in shaping the prospects for poor communities and households to defend the resources upon which their livelihoods depend? Ruth Meinzen-Dick joined IFPRI in 1989. She is Coordinator of the CGIAR program on Collective Action and Property Rights (CAPRi). Her research deals with water resource management, land, forests, property rights, collective action, and the impact of agricultural research on poverty. She leads IFPRI’s Gender Task Force and co-leads work on strengthening women’s assets. Much of her research has been in South Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa. Rights, Resources, and Social Justice Speaker Series - Collective Action, Property Rights, and Development: Making the Links, Department of Environmental Studies | NYU                                         NEW YORK UNIVERSITY       ARTS AND SCIENCE       COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE       GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE                                     Printer Friendly                            Back to Events         Collective Action, Property Rights, and Development: Making the Links            ,     Location: 194 Mercer Street, Room 305   Property rights are all the rage in development circles. But what are the real links between property rights and sustainable livelihoods for the poor? And what kind of property rights are we talking about? What role does collective action have in shaping the prospects for poor communities and households to defend the resources upon which their livelihoods depend? Ruth Meinzen-Dick joined IFPRI in 1989. She is Coordinator of the CGIAR program on Collective Action and Property Rights (CAPRi). Her research deals with water resource management, land, forests, property rights, collective action, and the impact of agricultural research on poverty. She leads IFPRI’s Gender Task Force and co-leads work on strengthening women’s assets. Much of her research has been in South Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa.
